ehpi 0.7.0

An interface to eight compartmental epidemic models.

Source: R/epi.R
epi.Rd

epi() is an application programming interface (for the Shiny application that motivated its creation) or a convenient function for interactive use in epidemic modelling. The arguments provided to the function determine compartments used in the model that is run.

Usage

epi(
  population,
  susceptible,
  exposed = 0,
  infected,
  recovered,
  dead = 0,
  beta,
  gamma,
  sigma = 0,
  delta = 0,
  xi = 0,
  muB = 0,
  muD = 0,
  vitalDynamics = FALSE,
  trueMassAction = FALSE,
  timesteps = 25,
  timeIncrement = 1
)

Arguments

population

The initial number of persons in the simulation; if vitalDynamics = TRUE and muB and muD are equal, then it is constant.

susceptible

The initial number of people who are susceptible to the disease (they have no natural immunity to it).

exposed

The initial number of people who have been exposed to the infection and may become infectious themselves.

infected

The initial number of people who are infectious and may infect others.

recovered

The initial number of people whom are no longer infectious and not a risk to others.

dead

The initial number of fatalities (people killed by the disease).

beta

The rate of becoming infectious (if sigma = 0, the default), or the rate of susceptible people being exposed to the infectious.

gamma

The rate of becoming recovered (no longer infectious, if sigma = 0, the default), or the rate of becoming infectious after exposure.

sigma

The rate of becoming recovered (no longer infectious).

delta

The rate of fatality.

xi

The rate of loss of learned immunity.

muB

The rate of birth.

muD

The rate of death not due to the disease under consideration.

vitalDynamics

Whether vital dynamics is enabled (if FALSE, the default, implies muB and muD of zero).

trueMassAction

Whether the force of infection is scaled by the population or not.

timesteps

The number of output rows in the simulation.

timeIncrement

The number of increments of "time" that pass between each output row.

Value

A dataframe with a column for each enabled compartment and a column for time, with timesteps rows. Each row contains the values of the differential equations for each point in time of the model (per function arguments).

Details

The convention for pronouncing epi() is "epi epi" as if you were saying "epidemic" twice. If you do want to refer to the package alone, and not the singular function it packages, you can say "eh pee eye", like "API".

"eh pee eye" is a tongue-in-cheek Canadianism. You might understand it as, "Eh, P.I.?", or just a Canadian slant on API. The latter was thought of first.

While ehpi provides "an API" for the Episim Shiny application, it won't enable the development of applications that provide any feature episim doesn't already provide by wrapping this package. The function is packages was extracted from that project to allow associating well-formatted documentation, vignettes, and examples with the function because that function is expected to be used outside of Episim, interactively, during workshops run by Dr. Krishnamurthy.

Examples

epi(population = 500,
    susceptible = 489,
    exposed = 10,
    infected = 1,
    recovered = 0,
    dead = 29,
    beta = 0.005,
    gamma = 0.0009,
    sigma = 0.000001,
    delta = 0.01,
    timesteps = 230)
